steps.description:
Pour a single layer of clams into the bottom of the saucepan and stir until the clams are coated with the garlic butter. You will need to cook the clams in batches. Do not stack the clams on top of each other in the pan since doing so will make it difficult for any clams on the bottom layer to open. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Cook-Clams-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Cook-Clams-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Stirring and coating the clams helps to ensure that the heat will be evenly distributed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fa/Cook-Clams-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fa/Cook-Clams-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Let the clams cook for roughly 4 minutes before removing the cover. The clams are finished once they open. Clams only open when they are completely cooked. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d6/Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d6/Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If any clams have not opened, remove the clams that have opened and continue cooking the unopened clams for another 1 to 2 minutes. If the clams still do not open, discard them, since they might be bad. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/59/Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/59/Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Avoid over-cooking the clams since doing so will cause them to become tough. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d3/Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d3/Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If the clams are still in their shells, remove them before frying them. Place the clams in a freezer for five minutes so that the meat loosens from the shell. Hold the clam in one hand with the shell hinge toward your palm. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9c/Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9c/Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Insert a dull knife in between the shell. Saw around the shell until you cut through the hinge and open the shell. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1a/Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1a/Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Slide the knife in between the clam meat and the top and bottom shell to remove the meat. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Let each clam drain slightly as you pull it out from the milk mixture. Then, toss each clam into the flour mixture and dredge until all sides are coated. To drain the clams, simply hold each one above the bowl for roughly 30 seconds or until you no longer notice liquid dripping off. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b7/Cook-Clams-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b7/Cook-Clams-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You can use your fingers or a pair of tongs to dredge the clams. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Cook-Clams-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Cook-Clams-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove the clams from their shells if they are still intact. Let the clams sit in a freezer for five minutes or until the meat loosens from the shell. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/df/Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/df/Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

While holding the clam in one hand, with the shell hinge toward your palm, insert a dull knife into the shell. Saw around the perimeter of the shell until you cut through the hinge. Open the shell with your fingers{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/87/Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/87/Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Slide the knife in between the clam meat and the top and bottom shells. Transfer the meat to a separate dish and discard the shells. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/34/Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/34/Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-14Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Combine the bread crumbs, Parmesan cheese, lemon juice, lemon zest, pesto, parsley, and olive oil in a bowl. Add half of the clarified butter or melted unsalted butter and mix together until moist. While the stuffing mix should be moist, it should not be dripping wet or soaked. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1b/Cook-Clams-Step-24Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-24Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1b/Cook-Clams-Step-24Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-24Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Only add the remaining butter if necessary, and do so 1 Tbsp (15 mL) at a time to avoid over-soaking the stuffing mix. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a9/Cook-Clams-Step-24Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-24Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a9/Cook-Clams-Step-24Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-24Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove the clams from the water and pry them open with your fingers. Stuff the clams with enough of the stuffing mix to cover the meat completely. If you cannot open the clams with your fingers, glide a thin, dull knife in between the shell halves and cut around the perimeter until loosened. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b9/Cook-Clams-Step-25Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-25Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b9/Cook-Clams-Step-25Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-25Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Position the stuffed clams on your prepared baking sheet. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2e/Cook-Clams-Step-25Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-Clams-Step-25Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2e/Cook-Clams-Step-25Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-Clams-Step-25Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
